Parity Problem...

Our task will consist of the solution to the even/odd parity determination for a binary sequence. For example, if we have the binary sequence 1010111001, then we have an even number of ones and the sequence has even parity. For the sequence 1011111001, we have an odd number of ones and the sequence has odd parity. However, turning this into an iterative problem means we move from the left to the right and decide to map each digit to even (0) or odd (1), based on whether we have encountered an even or odd number of ones so far in the sequence:

Input: 1 0 1 0 1 1 1 0 0 1
Output: 1 1 0 0 1 0 1 1 1 0

or for the second sequence:

Input: 1 0 1 1 1 1 1 0 0 1
Output: 1 1 0 1 0 1 0 0 0 1

By constructing the task in this way, we can now use the information above to construct the three major categories of sequence learning tasks: Many-to-One, Many-to-Many, and One-to-Many:

  • Many-to-One: The network will be provided with the entire input sequence, but only predict the last output bit above. This is essentially just using the recurrent memory to keep track of the sequence information and then predict even/odd parity only at the end of observing the sequence (0 and 1, respectively, become the targets for the two sequences above).
  • Many-to-Many: The network will be provided with the entire input sequence, but on each digit presentation, the corresponding output digit will be provided on each step in the sequence as a corresponding target.
  • One-to-Many: The network will only be provided the last digit of the input sequence, but will then be required to produce the entire output sequence (which serves as the targets) based on this single input bit. Note that we could choose the first bit of the input sequence instead of the last. It really makes no difference in this case because this task is ill-posed: there is no way to predict a sequence of bits from a single input bit. So, we expect poor performance on this task, but it does illustrate how to construct a model which can process data in a One-to-Many fashion and this model structure will be effective for other tasks which we will tackle in the future.

class ParityProblemDataModule(pl.LightningDataModule):
    def __init__(self,
                 batch_size = 50,
                 n_sequences = 1000,
                 n_timesteps = 20,
                 val_split = 0.2,
                 num_workers = 4,
                 problem = 'Many2One',
                 **kwargs):
        super().__init__(**kwargs)
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.n_sequences = n_sequences
        self.n_timesteps = n_timesteps
        self.val_split = val_split
        self.num_workers = num_workers
        self.problem = problem
        self.input_shape = None
        self.output_shape = None
        self.data_train = None
        self.data_val = None
        self.data_test = None

    def setup(self, stage: str):
        if (stage == 'fit' or \
            stage == 'validate') and \
            not(self.data_train and self.data_val):
            rng = np.random.default_rng()
            X = rng.integers(0,2,size=(self.n_sequences,self.n_timesteps))
            Y = np.cumsum(X,1) % 2
            if self.problem == 'One2Many':
                X = X[:,self.n_timesteps-1]
            if self.problem == 'Many2One':
                Y = Y[:,self.n_timesteps-1]
            self.input_shape = X.shape[1:]
            self.output_shape = Y.shape[1:]
            split_point = int(X.shape[0]*(1.0-self.val_split))
            self.data_train = list(zip(torch.Tensor(X[:split_point]).to(torch.long),
                                       torch.Tensor(Y[:split_point]).to(torch.long)))
            self.data_val = list(zip(torch.Tensor(X[split_point:]).to(torch.long),
                                     torch.Tensor(Y[split_point:]).to(torch.long)))
        if (stage == 'test' or \
            stage == 'predict') and \
            not self.data_test:
            rng = np.random.default_rng()
            X = rng.integers(0,2,size=(self.n_sequences,self.n_timesteps))
            Y = np.cumsum(X,1) % 2
            if self.problem == 'One2Many':
                X = X[:,self.n_timesteps-1]
            if self.problem == 'Many2One':
                Y = Y[:,self.n_timesteps-1]
            self.input_shape = X.shape[1:]
            self.output_shape = Y.shape[1:]
            self.data_test = list(zip(torch.Tensor(X).to(torch.long),
                                      torch.Tensor(Y).to(torch.long)))
            
    def train_dataloader(self):
        return torch.utils.data.DataLoader(self.data_train,
                                           batch_size=self.batch_size,
                                           num_workers=self.num_workers,
                                           shuffle=True)

    def val_dataloader(self):
        return torch.utils.data.DataLoader(self.data_val,
                                           batch_size=self.batch_size,
                                           num_workers=self.num_workers,
                                           shuffle=False)

    def test_dataloader(self):
        return torch.utils.data.DataLoader(self.data_test,
                                           batch_size=self.batch_size,
                                           num_workers=self.num_workers,
                                           shuffle=False)

    def predict_dataloader(self):
        return torch.utils.data.DataLoader(self.data_test,
                                           batch_size=self.batch_size,
                                           num_workers=self.num_workers,
                                           shuffle=False)

Model Building

TL;DR - The code snippet which follows is just an illustration of a coding concept used in the boilerplate. This changes the boilerplate in a key way from prior boilerplate that you have seen so far this semester, so you should use the new boilerplate from now on and not the old.

All metrics (loss, accuracy, etc.) calculate along the first dimension after the batch dimension (so, really the second dimension). For complex time-series or convolutional time-series tasks, output tensors are typically multidimensional and calculate logits on the last dimension instead. So, we have to permute the last dimension to the second dimension in order for metrics to be properly calculated. In boilerplate code that I have provided previously this semester, this was taken for granted since the logits were always in the second dimension of the output tensor. Below is a quick example of how to always permute the last dimension to the second dimension (and also covers the case where the second dimension is already the last dimension). Read the documentation for the loss and accuracy metrics carefully for this detail if you want to know why we need to do this. Note that the next few lines of code just illustrate the concept, and then this concept is used in the boilerplate class as-needed.

In [14]:
# Define Trainable Module (Abstract Base Class)
class LightningBoilerplate(pl.LightningModule):
    def __init__(self, **kwargs):
        super().__init__(**kwargs) # Call the super class constructor
        
    def predict_step(self, predict_batch, batch_idx):
        x, y_true = predict_batch
        y_pred = self.predict(x)
        return y_pred, y_true

    def training_step(self, train_batch, batch_idx):
        x, y_true = train_batch
        y_pred = self(x)
        perm = (0,-1) + tuple(range(y_pred.ndim))[1:-1]
        for metric_name, metric_function in self.network_metrics.items():
            metric_value = metric_function(y_pred.permute(*perm),y_true)
            self.log('train_'+metric_name, metric_value, on_step=False, on_epoch=True)
        loss = self.network_loss(y_pred.permute(*perm),y_true)
        self.log('train_loss', loss, on_step=False, on_epoch=True)
        return loss
        
    def validation_step(self, val_batch, batch_idx):
        x, y_true = val_batch
        y_pred = self(x)
        perm = (0,-1) + tuple(range(y_pred.ndim))[1:-1]
        for metric_name, metric_function in self.network_metrics.items():
            metric_value = metric_function(y_pred.permute(*perm),y_true)
            self.log('val_'+metric_name, metric_value, on_step=False, on_epoch=True)
        loss = self.network_loss(y_pred.permute(*perm),y_true)
        self.log('val_loss', loss, on_step=False, on_epoch=True)
        return loss
        
    def test_step(self, test_batch, batch_idx):
        x, y_true = test_batch
        y_pred = self(x)
        perm = (0,-1) + tuple(range(y_pred.ndim))[1:-1]
        for metric_name, metric_function in self.network_metrics.items():
            metric_value = metric_function(y_pred.permute(*perm),y_true)
            self.log('test_'+metric_name, metric_value, on_step=False, on_epoch=True)
        loss = self.network_loss(y_pred.permute(*perm),y_true)
        self.log('test_loss', loss, on_step=False, on_epoch=True)
        return loss
In [15]:
# Attach loss, metrics, and optimizer
class MultiClassModule(LightningBoilerplate):
    def __init__(self,
                 num_classes,
                 **kwargs):
        super().__init__(**kwargs) # Call the super class constructor
        self.num_classes = num_classes

        # This creates an accuracy function
        self.network_metrics = torch.nn.ModuleDict({
            'acc': torchmetrics.classification.Accuracy(task='multiclass',
                                                        num_classes=num_classes)
        })
        # This creates a loss function
        self.network_loss = torch.nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

    def configure_optimizers(self):
        optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(self.parameters(), lr=0.001)
        return optimizer
In [16]:
class MultiClassNetwork(MultiClassModule):
    def __init__(self,
                 **kwargs):
        super().__init__(**kwargs)
        self.save_hyperparameters()
        
    def forward(self, x):
        y = x
        return y

Validate Encodings

The following section is all about validating the creation and use of random embeddings for the three tasks. It doesn't serve any other purpose, but does show how random embeddings are approximately mutually orthogonal vectors much like one-hot vectors are mutually orthogonal. So, random embeddings have similar mathematical properties to one-hot vector encodings but are much more memory-efficient than one-hot vector encodings.

In [19]:
class MultiClassNetwork(MultiClassModule):
    def __init__(self,
                 num_input_tokens,
                 hidden_size = 256,
                 num_hidden_layers = 6,
                 **kwargs):
        super().__init__(**kwargs)
        self.embedding = torch.nn.Embedding(num_input_tokens,
                                            hidden_size)

    def forward(self, x):
        y = x
        y = self.embedding(y)
        return y

class Many2OneNetwork(MultiClassModule):
    def __init__(self,
                 num_input_tokens,
                 hidden_size = 64,
                 **kwargs):
        super().__init__(**kwargs)
        self.save_hyperparameters()
        
        self.embedding = torch.nn.Embedding(num_input_tokens,
                                            hidden_size)
        self.rnn_layer = torch.nn.RNN(hidden_size,
                                      hidden_size)
        self.output_layer = torch.nn.Linear(hidden_size,
                                            self.num_classes)

    def forward(self, x):
        y = x
        y = self.embedding(y)
        y = self.rnn_layer(y.permute(1,0,2)) # Returns 2 tensors (as-tuple)
        y = self.output_layer(y[0][-1,:]) # Keep only the last
                                          # time-step...
        return y

class Many2ManyNetwork(MultiClassModule):
    def __init__(self,
                 num_input_tokens,
                 hidden_size = 64,
                 **kwargs):
        super().__init__(**kwargs)
        self.save_hyperparameters()
        
        self.embedding = torch.nn.Embedding(num_input_tokens,
                                            hidden_size)
        self.rnn_layer = torch.nn.RNN(hidden_size,
                                      hidden_size)
        self.output_layer = torch.nn.Linear(hidden_size,
                                            self.num_classes)

    def forward(self, x):
        y = x
        y = self.embedding(y)
        y = self.rnn_layer(y.permute(1,0,2)) # Returns 2 tensors (as-tuple)
        y = self.output_layer(y[0].permute(1,0,2)) # Keep all time-steps
        return y

In [62]:
class One2ManyNetwork(MultiClassModule):
    def __init__(self,
                 num_input_tokens,
                 num_output_timesteps,
                 hidden_size = 64,
                 **kwargs):
        super().__init__(**kwargs)
        self.save_hyperparameters()
        
        self.embedding = torch.nn.Embedding(num_input_tokens,
                                            hidden_size)
        self.rnn_layer = torch.nn.RNN(hidden_size,
                                      hidden_size)
        self.output_layer = torch.nn.Linear(hidden_size,
                                            self.num_classes)
        self.num_output_timesteps = num_output_timesteps

    def forward(self, x):
        y = x
        y = self.embedding(y).repeat(self.num_output_timesteps,1,1)
        y = self.rnn_layer(y) # Returns 2 tensors (as-tuple)
        y = self.output_layer(y[0].permute(1,0,2)) # Keep all time-steps
        return y
